  "prompt": "What is the main function of the brachiocephalic artery?",
  "response": "The **brachiocephalic artery** (also known as the brachiocephalic trunk or innominate artery) plays a crucial role in the circulatory system. Its **main function** is to **transport oxygen-rich blood from the aortic arch to the right side of the body**, specifically supplying:\n\n1. **Right Arm**: Through its continuation as the **right subclavian artery**, it provides blood to the right upper limb.\n2. **Right Side of the Head and Neck**: By dividing into the **right common carotid artery**, it delivers blood to the right side of the brain, face, and neck.\n\nIn summary, the brachiocephalic artery serves as a primary conduit for directing oxygenated blood from the heart to both the right arm and the right regions of the head and neck, ensuring these areas receive the necessary blood supply for their functions.",
